Class 4 Lab - Introduction to Thematic Mapping

source: https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~243578~5513495:North-America-Thematic-Maps-

Concepts & Themes:

This weeks lab will feature exploration of the following:

  • Classification methods

  • Table Joins

  • OTF (On the Fly) Projections

  • Basic Statistics Tools

Lab 4 Links:

During this weeks lab will utilize the following data & PDF guide:

  • Class 4 Lab PDF - Excercise 2+3 (Discover QGIS)

  • Class 4 Lab Data

    • lab.4.partI.pdf
    • lab.4.partII.pdf

Lab Steps:

In this second lab, we will explore essentials of thematic mapping across quantitative data types. We will utilize 3 separate mappings - one for US Census data; one for US States. In this last mapping, the basic statistic tool will be utilized.

Some of the topics covered in this lab:

  • Table joins

  • OTF (On the Fly) Projections

  • Classification Methods

  • Histograms & Summary Statistics

  • To start, download data needed for the lab from Class 4 Lab Data. Following the download, unzip the data and point QGIS to the data and secure a file path for the duration of the lab. Primary data download includes:

    • countyp010 geometry
    • ce2000t.dbf tabular data

  • Continue through Exercise 2 steps - lab.4.partI.pdf to complete a mapping of US Census data for county total population, lower 48 states (Task 1 + Task 2).

  • Once Exercise 2 mapping is complete, begin Exercise 3 - lab.4.partII.pdf. Primary data download includes:

    • nm_counties.qgz QGIS project loaded with New Mexico county geometries w/ POP2000 column and AVG_SALE87 column.

  • working within Task 5, 5.1 and 5.2, Statistics and Histograms within QGIS will be explored for POP2000 column and AVG_SALE87 columns.

No assignment deliverable is due for graded credit; this Lab is designed to orient and introduce the thematic mapping concepts and solutions to common thematic mapping challenges that will be useful for the graded Class 4 Assignment.

Further Reference:

  • Small Number Mapping example - heroin overdose per 100K population

  • Normalization Formulas for demographic data
